const schemaFaq = [
  {
    q: 'What is a healthy body fat percentage for men?',
    a: 'For adult men, the American Council on Exercise (ACE) classifies body fat as follows: essential fat 2–5%, athletes 6–13%, fitness 14–17%, acceptable 18–24%, and obese 25%+. Most health authorities consider 10–20% healthy for men aged 20–40, with acceptable ranges increasing slightly with age.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is a healthy body fat percentage for women?',
    a: 'Women naturally carry more essential fat due to hormonal and reproductive needs. ACE categories for women: essential fat 10–13%, athletes 14–20%, fitness 21–24%, acceptable 25–31%, and obese 32%+. A healthy range for women aged 20–40 is generally 18–28%, with ranges shifting slightly with age.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is essential body fat?',
    a: 'Essential fat is the minimum amount of fat required for normal physiological function — it supports hormone production, organ protection, vitamin absorption (A, D, E, K), and nervous system health. Men need at least 2–5% and women need 10–13% to maintain normal function. Falling below essential fat levels is medically dangerous.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is body fat percentage more accurate than BMI?',
    a: 'For assessing health risk, body fat percentage is generally more informative than BMI because it distinguishes between fat mass and muscle mass. BMI cannot identify "normal weight obesity" (healthy BMI but high fat) or correctly classify lean, muscular athletes. However, body fat measurement methods vary widely in accuracy, while BMI is quick and standardized.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How can I lower my body fat percentage?',
    a: 'The most evidence-based approach combines a moderate caloric deficit (300–500 kcal/day below TDEE) with resistance training to preserve muscle mass. Cardio accelerates the deficit. Aim to lose 0.5–1% body fat per month — faster rates risk muscle loss. Protein intake of 1.6–2.2 g/kg/day is critical to preserve lean mass during a cut.',
  },
];
